One man’s ‘magic’ is another man’s engineering. -Robert A. Heinlein
Is it possible to have your investments less buffeted by the winds of change or to own a portfolio that ‘defies gravity’ in a falling market?
The short answer is: yes. Constructing a portfolio to be insulated against wide market swings involves financial engineering and the application of economic theory.
Financial engineering concepts are used by Ravensview Capital as a suite of tools and models to balance a client’s portfolio and build appropriate hedges by applying mathematics, statistics and computational science.
Economics, as a science, grounds the use of our financial engineering methods in well researched theories of behavior and markets. Applied economics, as an art, enters a realm of forecasting and statistical probabilities where the possibilities of both opportunity and risk can be explored. Ravensview Capital seeks to best position a client for when theory meets reality; when now meets the future.
 
 
 
 



The Raven’s View
 

The raven operates under the principle of “Strategic Opportunism” and so does Ravensview Capital.
The basic two-fold premise behind professional arbitrage are the actions of positioning and striking. An assessment of probabilities for both opportunity and risk allows the client’s portfolio to best be positioned to be able to strike with success and achieve arbitrage.
The watchful raven views it’s surroundings to be unusually well positioned and quick to strike when the target avails itself. The raven is equally quick to take flight should the activity prove fruitless or excessively challenging.
Ravensview Capital actively manages it’s clients investments in a prudent manner that continually seeks opportunity while mitigating risk.


Who said: “there ain’t no such thing as a free lunch?”  (Actually, that was both Robert A. Heinlein and the economist Milton Friedman.)
As a mountaineer in the Cascade Mountains, Joe Eberhardt would notice that often when a climbing party would drop their backpacks and move even just 20’ away or so ravens would appear. First, the ravens would quietly swoop into position nearby and view the climbers for a bit. Then emboldened by the absence of the climbers from their packs a raven would venture forward and begin to open a loose pack flap to be rewarded with someone’s sack lunch. When the unfortunate climber returned to their pack they would find bits and pieces of the remains, but no lunch. Though not exactly free and requiring some small work on the raven’s part, the resulting arbitrage from positioning and striking was no less than professional and obviously the result of many successful past attempts. TANSTAAFL.

 
 
 
 



